Lithology prefix+name+suffix [read only]: serpentinite pebbly mud with lithic clasts
Clast comments: Dominant clasts are harzburgite 4-5 cm in size. Relic bastite in core but black rim abuot half cm thick has no visible relics. Subdominant mostly small serpentine chips or black chips

Dominant clasts are harzburgite 4-5 cm in size. Relic bastite in core but black rim abuot half cm thick has no visible relics. Subdominant mostly small serpentine chips or black chips. One large serpentine pebble about 2 cm long.

General interval comment: Darker blue grey than previous section. Minor uparching.
Clast comments: Dominant clast dark grey-black to lighter grey UM rocks. Subdom are small chips of pale green serpentine from veins.

General interval comment: Clast rich, very crowded with clasts. Verging on clast support. Color change to black blue-grey occurs in the MBIO sample, but must be rapid. Contrast with overlying mud flow is stark.
Clast comments: Dominant harzburgite clasts have thin black rims up to 5 mm thick. Subdom serpentine chips appear bleached to white-green color; tiny flecks throughout the core. Some of the white serpentine forms selvages on harzburgite, like broken vein.

General interval comment: clast rich 4-8 cmm thick rims on clasts.
Clast comments: Dominant harzburgite clasts have thin black rims up to 8 mm thick. Subdom serpentine chips appear bleached to white-green color; tiny flecks throughout the core. Some of the white serpentine forms selvages on harzburgite, like broken vein.
Matrix comments: Matrix slightly lighter color than overlying section (5) but still quite dark.

General interval comment: clast-poor, similar to section 3. clasts concentrated towards top of section.
Clast comments: Dominant clasts are harzburgitic, very dark olive grey. Can see bastites in cores, but rims are dark black, no relics. Most harzburgite clasts relatively fresh but some are greener, cut by wider serpentine veins, appear more serpentinized.

There are two large harzburgite clasts, one 4 x 6 cm, the other 3 x 4 cm. The larger clast has clear fresh pyroxene in center, not clear in smaller. Both are dark olive green with brick red oxidation; smaller clast more oxidized than larger one. The larger pale green serpentine chips are layered, suggesting vein fill.
Matrix comments: Matrix contains high proportion of sand and silt size material, looks to be small UM grains.

Clast comments: One small clast of harz
Matrix comments: Small rare crystals of euhedral calcite in matrix. Not aragonite.

Clast comments: Dom clasts are harzburgite with 4-5 mm bastites or Opx. No black rims on clasts. Subdom clasts include serpentine chips, small white clasts (silica-carbonate? rodingite?). One clast 3 x 3 cm is a breccia white two off-white rounded pieces cemented by pale green serpentine (?). Each clast contains small green serpentine inclusions. The off-white material may be silica-carbonate, or meta-mafic rock (rodingite).
Matrix comments: Rare crystals of euhedral calcite in matrix, up to 8 mm across. Not aragonite. Large crystal growth faces. Matrix has high content of sand-size clasts with range of colors, mostly dark, probably small UM fragments.

Clast comments: No large clasts. Biggest clast is about 1 cm long.
Matrix comments: Rare crystals of euhedral calcite in matrix, up to 8 mm across. Not aragonite. Large crystal growth faces. Matrix has high content of sand-size clasts with range of colors, mostly dark, probably small UM fragments.
